<title>The dream which Dia!kwain had before he received the tidings of the death of his father</title>
<summary><i>The dream of Díä!kwãin, before he received news of his father’s death. Further omens, etc. In the Katkop dialect by Díä!kwãin (L V.-15. 5110-5146).</i> Dia!kwain dreams that he and his father are cutting up a sheep and a Dutch man (&apos;Boer&apos;) threatens to beat them to death for killing the sheep. Dia!kwain awakes at daybreak and tells his wife that the dream had spoken like a person, of things that would come true. Dia!kwain&apos;s mother comes to tell him his father has died.</summary><comments>1) See also <i>What happens when we die</i>, 2) This story is found in Book V-15</comments><date>30 July – 5 August 1875</date><storypages>5110-5146</storypages><category>History (personal)</category><category>Relations with others</category><category>Portention</category><author>Dia!kwain (David Hoesar) (V)</author><keyword><kw>dream</kw><subkw>that Dia!kwain had before he heard of the death of his father</subkw></keyword>
